Part 3

The casualty door opened again.

This time...

a different doctor entered.

Younger than others.

White coat still looked new.

Stethoscope carefully placed around neck.

Not hanging carelessly like experienced doctors.

He walked towards the nurses' station.

Stopped.

Looked at the unusual crowd near ICU.

"What happened?"

The receptionist looked up.

"Road accident case."

"Anyone serious?"

"Old man."

"Name?"

The receptionist checked the register.

"Vikram Ahuja."

The doctor's hand stopped midway while signing the attendance sheet.

He looked up slowly.

"What?"

"Vikram Ahuja."

"Age?"

"Around fifty."

The doctor stood completely still.

The receptionist noticed.

"Sir...

you know him?"

No answer.

The doctor simply walked towards the ICU.

Slowly.

As though he was trying to remember something.

Or perhaps...

trying to forget.

---

Inside the ICU...

the old man remained unconscious.

Monitors beeped regularly.

IV drips continued.

Oxygen mask covered half his face.

The doctor stood outside the glass door.

Stared at the patient.

One minute passed.

Then another.

The senior nurse came beside him.

"Dr. Tripathy...

patient is stable now."

He didn't respond.

She looked at him carefully.

"You know him?"

He finally spoke.

Very softly.

"I don't know."

"What?"

"I knew someone..."

He stopped.

"Long time ago."

"Same name?"

"Yes."

"Same person?"

The doctor looked at the unconscious face.

Forehead bandaged.

Dried blood still visible near the ear.

White beard.

Wrinkled skin.

Old cotton shirt.

Rubber slippers kept under the stretcher.

"I don't know."

The nurse smiled slightly.

"Sir...

you're a doctor.

Check the file."

She handed him the case sheet.

He opened it.

Date of birth.

07-07-1977.

He calculated quickly.

Around fifty.

Matched.

Father's name.

Binay Ahuja.

His hand trembled slightly.

Address.

Unknown.

Occupation.

Unknown.

Relationship with attendant.

NGO Volunteer.

He closed the file.

Looked again at the old man.

Then quietly walked away.

The nurse called behind him.

"Sir...

you know him or not?"

He stopped near the exit.

Turned back.

"I knew someone named Vikram Ahuja."

"But..."

He looked one more time towards the ICU.

"...that Vikram would never become Budha Baba."

---

Dr. Adarsh Tripathy walked towards the canteen.

Not because he wanted tea.

Because he needed time to think.

The hospital canteen was always the same.

Old plastic chairs.

Stained tables.

One ceiling fan rotating slowly.

Tea that tasted exactly like yesterday's tea.

He sat in the corner.

Ordered nothing.

Simply stared at the wall.

*Vikram Ahuja.*

*Binay Ahuja.*

*Date of birth 07-07-1977.*

Everything matched.

Yet everything felt wrong.

That Vikram wore branded clothes.

This Budha Baba wore torn cotton.

That Vikram was always surrounded by friends.

This old man was brought by an NGO volunteer.

That Vikram talked about building companies.

This man...

apparently told crow stories to school children.

The tea seller came to his table anyway.

"Sir...

regular?"

Adarsh nodded without looking.

The tea arrived.

He held the glass.

Felt the warmth.

Remembered.

---

*Twenty-eight years ago.*

*1995.*

*The year everything began.*

---

He was eighteen then.

First year MBBS.

Anatomy practical.

The dissection hall smelled exactly how dissection halls always smell.

Formaldehyde.

Steel trays.

A chart of the human skeleton on the wall.

Forty students.

Ten dissection tables.

Complete chaos.

"Where is my scalpel?"

"Who took the forceps?"

"Sir...

the specimen is missing a label."

"Careful...

careful..."

Someone knocked over a jar.

Laughter.

Then scolding.

Then normal again.

Adarsh stood near table seven.

Alone.

His partner hadn't arrived yet.

The lab assistant distributed white aprons.

"Wear properly."

"This is not chemistry.

Respect the body."

"Breakage of instruments will be charged."

Nobody listened completely.

Everyone wore aprons carelessly.

Except one boy.

He wore it carefully.

Tied the strings properly.

Checked the pockets.

Then quietly walked towards table seven.

Looked at Adarsh.

"Partner?"

Adarsh nodded.

The boy smiled slightly.

Extended his hand.

"Vicky."

Adarsh shook hands.

"Adarsh."

"Tripathy?"

Adarsh was surprised.

"How do you know?"

Vicky pointed at the apron.

On the left pocket...

someone had stitched a name using blue thread.

**Adarsh Tripathy**

Small letters.

Neat stitching.

Mother's handiwork.

Adarsh felt embarrassed.

"My mother..."

Vicky's smile changed.

"My mom would have done the same."

A pause.

"But she is no more with me."

Adarsh didn't know what to say.

"Lost her.

Never seen."

Vicky's eyes went somewhere else.

Almost wet.

Then he blinked.

Came back.

Picked up the scalpel.

Checked its edge against the light.

Just like that.

Emotion appeared.

Then disappeared.

Adarsh said nothing.

"Sorry" felt too small.

They began the dissection.

Cutting.

Observing.

Labeling.

Very little conversation.

Just enough.

"Pass the forceps."

"Done?"

"Wait."

Midway through the practical...

the lab assistant shouted.

"Five minutes remaining."

Everyone hurried.

Mistakes increased.

Confusion increased.

Vicky remained calm.

Completed every step properly.

No hurry.

Adarsh noticed.

This boy was different.

Not showing off.

Simply focused.

Professor Khanna walked between the tables.

White beard.

Reputation for failing half the class.

He stopped at table seven.

Read the stitched name aloud.

"Adarsh Tripathy."

Adarsh froze.

"Your mother did this?"

"Yes, sir."

A pause.

Then the professor smiled.

"Good.

At least someone's mother believes her son will pass my class."

Scattered laughter.

He moved on.

Vicky whispered.

"Saved you."

"Saved me?

He announced it to the whole hall."

"Better than announcing you can't hold a scalpel properly."

Fair point.

---

The bell rang.

"Submit your observations."

Everyone rushed towards the professor's desk.

Vicky and Adarsh submitted together.

Khanna checked.

Nodded.

"Good."

They removed their aprons.

Kept them on the rack.

Then walked out.

Outside the hall...

someone called.

"Aye...

first year."

Four seniors stood near the staircase.

Second year students.

Ragging season.

Adarsh felt nervous.

Vicky remained calm.

The seniors walked closer.

"Name?"

Adarsh answered immediately.

"Adarsh Tripathy."

One senior laughed.

"Tripathy...

Brahmin?"

"Yes."

"Bad luck.

General category.

No quota, no backup.

Pure merit for you, poor fellow."

Everyone laughed.

Adarsh said nothing.

Then they turned to Vicky.

"You?"

"Vicky."

The senior blinked.

"Vicky?"

He turned to the others.

"*Vicky?*

That's a dog's name, yaar.

My cousin's Pomeranian is called Vicky."

Everyone laughed harder.

Vicky's face didn't change.

"Full name."

A pause.

Then he answered.

"Vikram Ahuja."

The laughter stopped.

"Ahuja...

business family?"

Vikram didn't answer.

The senior pressed.

"Rich family?"

"I don't know."

"You don't know if your family is rich?"

Laughter again.

Another senior interrupted.

"Arre leave him.

Look at his shoes.

Nike.

Definitely rich."

Vikram looked at his shoes.

Then at Adarsh's cheap rubber slippers.

He felt uncomfortable.

Not because of seniors.

Because of the comparison.

One senior stepped closer.

"First year riddle.

Answer fast."

Vikram waited.

"Which part of the body...

has no bone...

full flesh...

but most sensitive?

Nerve endings everywhere."

Silence.

Vikram's ears went red.

He looked at the ground.

Didn't answer.

Adarsh understood the trap.

Tried to help.

Pulled his own tongue out.

Wiggled it.

Pointed.

The seniors burst out laughing.

"Oye!

Pervert!

It's the tongue, man!

What were *you* thinking?"

Vikram's face went from red to redder.

"I... I knew that."

"Sure you did."

More laughter.

The senior wasn't finished.

"Next one.

Which part...

if you put a finger inside...

water comes out?"

Vikram, still flustered, blurted the first thing.

"Eye."

The seniors erupted.

"Eye?

Bro!

Should I put my finger in your eye and check?

Let's see how much water comes out."

Laughter loud enough for two floors below.

Even Adarsh laughed this time.

Vikram's ears stayed red.

Then he laughed too.

Small.

Reluctant.

But real.

The senior turned to Adarsh.

"You.

Sing a song."

Adarsh's throat closed.

He sang two lines.

Badly.

"Enough.

Terrible voice.

Go."

They didn't dismiss Vikram.

"You.

Stay."

Vikram glanced at Adarsh.

A small shake of the head.

*Go.*

Adarsh walked a few steps.

Slowed down.

Listened.

"Rich boy.

You think your papa's money matters here?"

"No."

"Good.

Remember that."

Footsteps.

Vikram caught up near the gate.

Neither spoke for a while.

Then Adarsh asked.

"Your name...

Bikram or Vikram?"

"Vikram."

"Why did you say Vicky?"

Vikram smiled.

Small.

Tired.

"Everyone calls me Vicky."

"Why?"

"Easier."

They reached the canteen.

Ordered tea.

Sat on the wooden bench outside.

Afternoon sun.

Tree shade.

Neither spoke for a while.

First day of friendship.

Neither of them knew then...

that this friendship would last almost three decades.

Neither of them knew...

that one day Adarsh would stand in a hospital corridor,

staring at an unconscious old man,

trying to believe that Vicky and Budha Baba were the same person.

---

Dr. Adarsh Tripathy opened his eyes.

The hospital canteen returned.

His tea had become cold.

He hadn't taken a single sip.

The tea seller asked.

"Sir...

shall I change it?"

Adarsh looked at the glass.

Shook his head.

"No."

He stood up.

Walked back towards the casualty.

The crowd near ICU had grown even larger.

Someone had brought flowers.

Someone had brought fruits.

A small child held a hand-drawn greeting card.

The NGO girl still sat on the same chair.

Holding the walking stick.

Waiting.

Adarsh stood at a distance.

Watched everything.

Then slowly walked towards the ICU door.

The nurse saw him.

"Sir...

did you remember?"

He nodded.

"College friend."

"You are sure?"

"Same name.

Same father's name.

Same date of birth."

"Then why did you say you don't know?"

Adarsh looked through the glass at the unconscious man.

"Because..."

He stopped.

How could he explain?

The Vikram he knew...

was supposed to become something else.

Not this.

The nurse waited for the answer.

Adarsh simply said.

"Because I don't know what happened between then and now."

He walked away.

But his mind remained inside the ICU.

---

That evening...

Budha Baba's condition improved.

Blood transfusion completed.

Bleeding stopped.

Vitals stable.

The senior doctor allowed one visitor.

The NGO girl immediately stood up.

She entered the ICU.

Stood beside the bed.

Looked at the old man.

His eyes remained closed.

But breathing had become normal.

She didn't say anything.

Simply kept her hand on his.

Very softly.

As though reassuring herself he was still alive.

After two minutes...

she quietly left.

Outside...

the entire crowd looked at her.

Waiting for news.

She smiled.

"He is better."

Relief.

Immediately...

the little boy shouted.

"Baba will tell the crow story now!"

Everyone smiled.

Even the serious-looking security guard.

The NGO girl sat back on her chair.

This time...

she finally noticed her own injury.

Blood had dried on her elbow.

The sleeve was torn.

She hadn't even cleaned it.

A nurse came with cotton and Dettol.

"Let me see."

The girl hesitated.

The nurse understood.

"I know.

AIDS.

I'll be careful."

She cleaned the wound.

Applied bandage.

"You should have treated this first."

The girl smiled.

"Baba was more important."

"Why?"

The girl looked towards the ICU.

"Because..."

She tried to find words.

"...he taught me that life is bigger than diseases."

The nurse didn't understand completely.

But she didn't ask more.

---

Dr. Adarsh Tripathy completed his duty at 8 PM.

Signed the register.

Removed his white coat.

But didn't leave immediately.

He walked back towards the ICU one more time.

The crowd had reduced slightly.

But the NGO girl still remained.

He stood beside her.

She looked up.

"Doctor sahib...

he will recover na?"

Adarsh nodded.

"He will."

"When can we take him home?"

"Few days."

She nodded.

Relieved.

Adarsh hesitated.

Then asked.

"You know him since long?"

"Three years."

"How did you meet him?"

She smiled.

"He came to our NGO.

Said he wants to teach children.

No salary.

Just time pass."

Adarsh felt strange hearing this.

Vikram Ahuja.

Son of Binay Ahuja.

Teaching children.

Time pass.

Something didn't fit.

"What does he teach?"

"Everything.

Maths.

Science.

Stories.

Life."

"Where does he live?"

"Near the NGO.

Small room."

"Alone?"

"Yes."

"No family?"

The girl thought for a moment.

"Baba never talks about family."

Adarsh wanted to ask more.

But he stopped.

Instead he asked something else.

"What is your name?"

"Ananya."

"You work in NGO?"

"Yes.

HIV awareness program."

Adarsh understood why she had AIDS.

Probably contracted during awareness work.

Or perhaps before joining.

He didn't ask.

Some questions remain unasked.

"Thank you for bringing him here."

Ananya smiled.

"I should thank him.

He brought me here three years ago.

Same hospital.

Different reason."

Adarsh didn't understand.

She continued.

"When I got HIV report...

I tried to end my life.

Pills.

Hospital.

Stomach wash.

Baba was the only one who visited.

Every single day.

Until I walked out alive."

She looked at Adarsh.

"Today...

I returned the favor."

Adarsh said nothing.

Simply nodded.

Then quietly left.

---

Outside the hospital...

the night had become completely dark.

Auto rickshaws honked.

Street vendors shouted.

Normal city life.

Adarsh stood near the gate.

Tried to process everything.

*Vikram Ahuja.*

*Budha Baba.*

*Same person.*

*Different life.*

*What happened?*

He knew only one thing clearly.

Tomorrow...

when Vikram wakes up...

he will ask.

Not as a doctor.

As an old friend.

---

Back in the ICU...

around 11 PM...

something changed.

The monitor beeped differently.

The duty nurse noticed.

Checked vitals.

Then smiled.

Patient was waking up.

She informed the senior doctor.

He came immediately.

Checked everything.

"Good.

Consciousness returning.

Keep monitoring."

Around 11:30 PM...

the old man's eyes slowly opened.

First confused.

Then focused.

He saw the white ceiling.

Hospital smell.

Beeping machines.

He tried to remember.

Road.

Auto.

Sudden crash.

Children screaming.

Ananya's voice.

Then darkness.

He tried to speak.

Nothing came out.

Throat dry.

The nurse came closer.

"Baba...

you are in hospital.

Don't worry.

You are safe now."

He blinked.

Trying to understand.

She gave him water.

Few drops.

He drank slowly.

Then whispered.

"Ananya?"

"Outside.

Waiting."

He tried to sit.

"Careful Baba."

He lay back.

Closed his eyes again.

But this time...

not unconscious.

Just tired.

Very tired.

The nurse stepped out.

Told Ananya.

"He woke up.

Asked for you."

Ananya smiled.

Tears came suddenly.

Relief.

She didn't enter.

Just folded her hands towards the ICU.

"Thank you."

To whom?

God?

Doctors?

Life itself?

Nobody knew.

Perhaps she herself didn't know.

---

That night...

Dr. Adarsh couldn't sleep.

He kept thinking.

*Vikram Ahuja.*

*07-07-1977.*

*Chemistry lab.*

*White apron.*

*Mother's stitched name.*

*First meeting.*

*Then what?*

*What happened after college?*

*Where did he go?*

*Why didn't they stay in touch?*

*How did Vikram become Budha Baba?*

Questions without answers.

He knew tomorrow he would get some answers.

But he also knew...

some questions would remain forever.

Because...

the distance between a college laboratory and a hospital ICU...

is never just years.

Sometimes...

it's an entire lifetime.

---

[End of Part 3]
